AU  - Parra, Fabian
AU  - Valner, Robert
AU  - Kruusamaee, Karl
AU  - Pryor, Mitch
TI  - Unlocking underrepresented use-cases for large language model-driven human-robot task planning
T2  - ADVANCED ROBOTICS
M3  - Article
AB  - Large language models (LLM) are now the de facto task planners for Embodied AI (EAI) systems. This shift can be attributed to LLMs' powerful, emergent properties which enable their adaptation to downstream tasks with minimal to no fine tuning via prompting. However, we find that LLM-driven task planning is not a solved problem. In this work we measure the extent to which these models can be adapted to complex and domain-specific task planning via few-shot prompting. Additionally, we contribute quantitative and qualitative analysis on prompt robustness. Lastly, to meet the challenges of adapting EAI systems to real-world, industrial domains, we adopt a human-in-the-loop approach to guarantee safe and interpretable task planning and execution. We successfully demonstrate co-located, human-robot teaming where an Augmented Reality (AR) headset mediates information exchanged between an EAI agent and human operator for a variety of inspection tasks. To our knowledge the use of an AR headset for multimodal grounding and the application of EAI to industrial tasks are novel contributions within Embodied AI research.
