AU  - Xi, Dinghao
AU  - Li, Zhiyu
AU  - Zhao, Jinxiang
AU  - Xu, Wei
TI  - Detecting LLM-generated peer reviews: A syntactic-semantic collaborative framework with rhetorical structure analysis
T2  - INFORMATION SCIENCES
M3  - Article
AB  - Large language models (LLMs) are transforming academic peer review by boosting efficiency, yet raising concerns about authorship authenticity and scholarly integrity. Current detection methods, designed for general text, struggle to capture the specialized linguistic patterns of peer review. To address these challenges, we propose a Syntactic-Semantic Collaborative Framework (SSCF), which combines cross-document syntactic features with semantic representations tailored to peer review discourse. As a core component within the framework, we propose RSTGraphNet, a hierarchical graph-based module that captures the rhetorical structure of peer reviews as discourse-level semantic features. We further introduce entity-consistency features to ensure coherence between the review and its source manuscript. To address data scarcity, we construct a comprehensive dataset comprising human and LLM-generated peer reviews, synthesized through diverse prompting strategies across six representative LLMs. Extensive experiments validate the effectiveness of SSCF (F1-Score: 0.9586), significantly outperforming state-of-the-art baselines. The framework also demonstrates strong generalization across datasets, yielding minimal false positives on human reviews. This research lays the groundwork for safeguarding the integrity of peer review through automated content authentication in scholarly publishing.
